# 5. Input System (input.js)

This file tracks keyboard input.

Two event listeners are used:

keydown  
keyup

When a key is pressed the system records it inside an object:

keys[key] = true

When released:

keys[key] = false

Players read these values every frame.

Example:

if (keys["A"]) {  
  move player left  
}

---

# 6. Player System (player.js)

This file controls player movement, jumping, and animation.

Each player object contains:

x → horizontal position  
y → vertical position  
vx → horizontal velocity  
vy → vertical velocity  
w → player width  
h → player height

Movement works by modifying velocity.

Example logic:

Press left → vx decreases  
Press right → vx increases

Jumping sets a negative vertical velocity.

vy = -jumpForce

Gravity then pulls the player back down.

vy += gravity

---

# 7. Physics System (physics.js)

The physics system is responsible for:

• gravity  
• platform collisions  
• player blocking  
• player stacking

Collision detection uses **Axis Aligned Bounding Boxes (AABB)**.

Collision condition example:

playerRight > platformLeft  
playerLeft < platformRight  
playerBottom > platformTop  
playerTop < platformBottom

If a collision happens the player's position is corrected.

Example:

player.y = platform.y - player.h  
player.vy = 0

This prevents objects from overlapping.

---

# 8. Player Interaction Mechanics

Players can interact with each other in two ways.

Player Blocking

Players cannot pass through each other horizontally.

Player Stacking

If one player lands on another player's head they stand on top of them.

This mechanic allows puzzles that require vertical cooperation.

